sentence: On CNBC's "Options Action," Carter Worth shared with the viewers his bearish point of view of Procter & Gamble Co (NYSE: PG).
He thinks the stock is a bit hot, as it has significantly outperformed its peers.
Over the last year it gained 24%, while XLP gained only 10%.
In the last five years it jumped 93% and the consumer staples ETF added only 33%.
Procter & Gamble is so much ahead of its sector that it would be right to take profits or reduce exposure, Worth said.
Mike Khouw wants to use a put spread diagonal to make a bearish trade.
He wants to buy the January $145 put for $6.25 and sell the November $140 put for $2.25.
The total cost for the trade would be $4.

Khouw is selling the November expiration put because the implied volatility is elevated in the short term and he doesn't expect a sharp move lower after the earnings report, which is scheduled for Tuesday.
